<subSubSection id="A75CA730D2E1AC1B091E8EF8462E937C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CE3476627D1F169F4007844A7151C74F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B5EE126FFEC4E4F3951A1A591E49404" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
1.35-5.2 mm, 2.0-3.5
<normalizedToken id="30F98A5E2FAFDF51606370B40271807E" originalValue="Ã—">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide. 
<taxonomicName id="A24F01F7DECC2825948F89BA4F77A935" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Arixyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Arixyleborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2C4936B0C200171C7B7087693D5B661C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Arixyleborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the elytra with distinctive deep strial furrows and interstrial ridges, ridges either granulate or carinate (three species without). 
<taxonomicName id="C4CDDFE8BA8AD97CC5401783A43A6057" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Arixyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Arixyleborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27EE8BD4BFBC612AB3F45FA1978F1C8F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Arixyleborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be further diagnosed by the obliquely truncate antennal club with segment 1 almost covering the posterior face (type 2), club wider than long or as long as wide; protibiae slender or evenly rounded, posterior face flat and unarmed or inflated and granulate; scutellum variable either flush with elytra and flat, flush with elytra and medially impressed or flat and depressed below elytra; elytra from dorsal view typically angulate apically, rarely rounded; mycangial tufts absent; and procoxae contiguous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C0C534B15C6145EF649D797B6C132731" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="2FE301E3ED13CA01D3416BE0E687C7EA" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Arixyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Arixyleborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B73E81738534977147ED7A905B2EC09B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Arixyleborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="EE441B8AC40C64F0CCC6FF021D96BEA3" authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2013" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Stictodex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stictodex" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E2524BE4C2D1246A7C085C5F8EDE5347" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Stictodex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with which it shares a broad antennal club but which lacks the distinctive elytral ridges and furrows. In addition, 
<taxonomicName id="793541299898959835991C277453FA34" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Arixyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Arixyleborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8CD446A791B4647BB6B99EAA99919741" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Arixyleborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has declivital striae 1 parallel to the suture while in 
<taxonomicName id="650049A5B04F7D8C5BA4CE6883E0A7E7" authority="Hulcr &amp; Cognato, 2013" authorityName="Hulcr &amp; Cognato" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Stictodex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Stictodex" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="236885E033B2048DF023ED17DFAEA5F6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Stictodex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are not parallel but undulating.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
